e. The surprising finding is that apparent conflicts involving religion and science reflect a more fundamental conflict between media elites and ordinary Americans over what is good debate. For elite representatives, good debate advances an agenda, but, as Evans shows, for many Americans it is defined by engagement and deliberation. This hidden conflict over what constitutes debate’s proper role diminishes the possibility for science and religion to be discussed meaningfully in public life. Challenging our understanding of science, religion, and conflict, Seeking Good Debate raises profound questions about the future of the public sphere and American democracy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aDebates and debatingzUnited States. 0aMass media and public opinionzUnited States. 0aPublic opinionzUnited States. 0aReligion and sciencexPublic opinion. 7aRELIGION / Religion & Science.2bisacsh  abioethics.  abiology.  achristian science.  achristian.  achristianity.  aenvironmental policy.  afaceless science.  afuture of religion.  afuture of science.  ahomosexuality.  ahuman origins.  amass media.  amediated discourse.  amedical science.  aphilosophy.  apolitics.  apublic policy.  areligion in america.  areligion in the public sphere.  areligion.  areligious credibility.  areligious discourse.  ascience and religion.  ascience in america.  ascience.  ascientific credibility.  ascientific discourse.  ascientific religion.  asocial history.  astem cell research.  astem cells.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z97831106675470 cprintz978052028507140uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052096066440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520960664423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/c